Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, the European powers were burning with a desire to penetrate deeply into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps only 20 steps from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial effort.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guidebooks say.
The building surrounds the end of the platforms, each with a tower at its front corner, and looks like a German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building's a little overwhelmed.
However, looking at the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious what the westernmost gate of a large-scale business was.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the “late future” of the conquests, wanted to achieve its ambitions to occupy the Middle East with the help of this railroad from Damascus through Baghdad to present-day Saudi Arabia.
German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and expelled the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria.
The Hyderpasha station was no better.
In 1917, a munitions train exploded and destroyed the beautifully constructed roof of the building.
According to Turkish sources, there was a sabotage operation.
Since then, it has slowly collapsed, and history has gone far beyond it.
At the same time, today, as the gateway to the railway to Anatolia and the whole of the eastern region, at least in a symbolic sense, it serves as Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon.
The Justice and Development Party in government - the AKP - has developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The new policy is characterised by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government maintains good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian groups of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq, Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded a night train to Ankara, the Turkish capital, to visit one of the AKP’s leading foreign policy experts, the Turkish parliamentarian Suat Kinikliogl.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of tumult, which at the time gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, "The Night Mail" - I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is intended as a symbol of the new secular state, which turns its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, which is known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This caused some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern building made of stone and steel, specifically designed for this purpose - a developing suburban area, half-finished shopping malls and coffee houses, where suited middle managers - both men and women - meet to do business early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have been a right-centered politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
“The party’s foreign policy goal is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has disrupted order," he said.
Turkey is isolated from its hinterland.
Today he had to turn east and west at the same time.
He couldn't choose between the two.
He had to open in both directions.
"But is it possible that sooner or later he will be forced to choose?" I asked.
“Turkey has never wanted to make a choice.”
He then emphasised what almost everyone I spoke to here almost mechanically repeated: Turkey’s relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the countries surrounding the Black Sea are just as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey itself.
It is as if they were trying to convey the message that, in a figurative sense, along with Turkey, the whole of Europe can reach Asia and the Middle East on those railroads going east.
When I was at Hydarpasha station again, after another night spent mostly awake, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conra, the two German gentlemen who had witnessed the reconstruction of this ornate structure a hundred years ago.
How they would have been surprised to learn that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in Turkey’s hands.
And as I waited at the port for the ferry to take me back through the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was called the "sick man of Europe" at the time.
At the time, there was no question as to which continent would claim this exciting country.
