In principle, only people under the age of 21 should have been included in the vocal arm, but when Proteus sang its finale in 1979 - many of us were in our late 20s - we simply refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the name of the mythological shape-shifter) was in line with the choir's determination and ability to cope with any score they put before it - be it a madrigal or a piece of the Messiah; unaccompanied or accompanied by a grand orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astounding and always exciting, and we owed it to the man whose inspiration has kept our enthusiasm for music unchanged over the years.
How often did Tod tell us to "let the music play by itself."
He always said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the score.
So sing it.”
His conductor technique has always been fully understandable and accurate, but it is never dictatorial or exaggerated.
Whatever the level of music, he always raised it.
John Frayn Turner wrote about it:
If there ever was a conductor who should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I got to know him well during the two decades he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past forty years I have written criticisms of more than 100 concerts, but I have never been disappointed by one of them, and I have often been enthralled with them.
Tod Handley had greatness and modesty together, which is very rare.
He hated those choirmasters who, in his words, simply "gapped around the world with a few well-known battlehorses."
Many of us will miss it.
