The collision-avoiding "bee car"
For the development of accident-prevention technologies, this time Nissan draws inspiration from nature, precisely from the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company has designed a robot that imitates the flight of bees to avoid accidents.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in the development of collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technology Center built this small robot in Japan in collaboration with the renowned Tokyo University’s Advanced Science and Technology Research Center.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Director of Technology PR and Research Development, defines the BR23C as an extension of Nissan’s four-level safety cover.
The robot enhances the collision avoidance capability of the company’s products.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety cover.
More importantly, however, the compound eye of the bee, with which it sees at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, is able to fly uninterrupted in its own personal space.
To replicate the function of the composite eye, the engineers designed a so-called laser range finder.
In a 180-degree field of view in front of the BR23C, the instrument detects obstacles within a distance of up to 2 meters, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately transformed into a collision avoidance operation.
"As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot mimics the movements of the uterus and immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid a collision.
What distinguishes the system from the currently available instruments is that in this case the avoidance manoeuvre takes place completely automatically.
If not, the robot would not be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, avoiding manoeuvres should not be directed up or down, nor diagonally, but only in two dimensions and only in the direction of the reversibility of the wheels, that is, not in an infinite direction and way, as is the case with bees.
That’s why Nissan used a rotary function in the robot, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, to avoid collisions.
“This structure only needs to process and respond to data every few seconds.
There is no need for data storage or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may sound surprising, but it’s not really gigabytes, but we’re not even talking about megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of an immediate collision prevention technology, which Nissan estimates could enter production vehicles within ten years.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, it may be possible to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to get the driver to the final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
