Rafael Correa's statement on Monday, Quito
The rebuilding of the republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is the common plan of Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
Following the example of his fellow presidents and friends, Correa explained his vision for the new constitution on Sunday.
His mission was successful, as 64% of the voters voted yes in the referendum, according to the official results, which covered 80% of the votes.
According to this, 28% of the population voted no, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% were cast unfilled.
A 50% + 1 vote was required to pass the draft Constitution.
On Sunday, two polls at the exit of the polling stations and a counting by a non-governmental organization both proved the overwhelming superiority of the "yes" votes at 63% and 70%, respectively.
Rafael Correa spoke of the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday.
"The Constitution has won an overwhelming victory," he said, thanking the Ecuadorians at Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As is well known, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Morales and Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.
According to a report by the Organization of American States (OAS) Observation Mission, the vote took place in a calm atmosphere. Its main theme was a 444-point text summarizing the principles of "new socialism" defended by the president.
The proposed constitution puts state power at the service of the economy, reserving the state the right to "plan development" for a country that essentially benefits from oil extraction by foreign companies and foreign currency sent by emigrants.
Correa’s draft constitution, which was elected in 2006, also confirms the power of the head of state, who can get a mandate for a maximum of two consecutive periods and is entitled to dissolve the parliament.
Correa has already announced that she will take advantage of this opportunity and will compete again in February 2009 for the mandate as Head of State.
The President has already begun to introduce free health services and education in his country, which has a population of 13.9 million and half of the population lives below the subsistence level.
Finally, the Constitution prohibits the presence of foreign troops in the country, which could put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of the Ecuadorian facility as a base for U.S. anti-drug measures.
19 hostages freed in Chad
An Egyptian commando attacked the kidnappers, who took 11 tourists and their eight companions hostage ten days ago.
The hostages are now in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and eight of their Egyptian escorts were detained in the desert for ten days, from where they were transported unharmed to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
The hostages were freed in Chad this morning by an Egyptian commando.
They arrived by plane at the al-Maza military base, which is directly linked to Cairo International Airport, at around half past three in the afternoon.
The hostages were forbidden to speak to the press and were immediately transferred to a hospital in Maadi, a suburban suburb of Cairo, where they were examined.
The hostages are "healthy" and the kidnappers "have not been paid a ransom," Egypt's tourism minister Zoheir Garanna said at the airport.
The hostages were taken hostage on 19 September at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border region of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they took part in an SUV safari.
The group consisted of 11 tourists (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman) and eight Egyptians: two tour guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, which organizes the safari.
According to one Egyptian security chief, a 30-member special force arrived on the scene in two helicopters, where the hostages were raided just before dawn.
"There was a firefight between the troops, half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled," the leader said.
He also said that a total of 150 special troops had been sent from the Egyptian Lightning Brigade to Sudan, where German and Italian SWAT troops were added.
Italian diplomat Franco Frattini, who is currently in Belgrade, stressed the role of secret agents and special Italian task forces.
“We have to admit that this result could not have been achieved without the professional and effective intervention of our intelligence personnel and task forces,” he said without further details.
He also denied paying ransom for the hostages.
The day before, the Sudanese army announced that it had intercepted an SUV with the kidnappers, killing six of them (including the Chadian leader) and arresting two of them.
The military said the hostages were linked to a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the organization immediately denied.
