Fox in the chicken coop
In the United States, life and health insurers often refuse to enter into an insurance contract with an applicant based on people’s drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a data protection program that requires the use of prescription data in all cases with the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in independent hands, otherwise we will leave the chicken coop to the fox," said Richard Dick, the developer of the program to track prescriptions.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the amount due in the event of damages dependent on the health of the applicant client, and if they consider the risk to be too high, they do not even take out insurance with it.
In the past, the person was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: pharmacies can easily get from a customer’s identification number what drugs they’ve bought in the past one and a half years, and the program itself infers what kind of disease they have and what their state of health is like.
For example, taking a high dose of cholesterol on a regular basis suggests that your blood fat levels are practically uncontrollably high, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of them also specify a risk multiplier number, so the insurer has little left to do outside the paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages are that some drugs can be used for multiple purposes, for example, some compounds can be used against migraines or hot flushes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is a significant risk-increasing factor for business insurers, while the former is not.
Separate companies have been formed to collect and process the data, and before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies, they ask for the patient’s consent.
They are now obliged to do so by the authorities, although no penalties have been imposed for their failure to act so far.
Some companies are now processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data to provide an even more accurate picture of patients’ health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and at the same time, it becomes increasingly difficult to control usage.
There is a separate Health Data Protection Act, but its scope is limited to healthcare providers and insurance companies.
There is a bill before Congress that gives the authorities control over companies that specialize in providing information.
Dick Richard understands that this is not enough; therefore, he has improved his program, which would require the explicit consent of the data subject to transmit the data.
Another issue is that the data subject can hardly refuse the consent, otherwise the insurers will not enter into a contract with him or her.
So the hens are somehow dependent on the goodwill of the fox.
Global menu of Marseille
India and the European Union are doubling trade
As the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, the agenda for the ninth summit was dominated by this subject, along with other, largely global, issues.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit, where nuclear cooperation will be discussed.
The European Union acknowledges that India is an emerging democratic power that should have a greater say in international affairs, but the member states have not yet managed to reach a common denominator on whether to support New Delhi's permanent membership in the UN Security Council.
This issue was not raised at the ninth summit held in Marseille yesterday.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, President-in-Office of the European Union, and Commission President José Manuel Barroso and High Representative for Foreign Affairs Javier Solana welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade in five years to more than <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>100 billion.
