The plane of billionaire Steve Fossett, who disappeared a year ago, was found.
They found the remains of the billionaire Steve Fossett's plane, who disappeared over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007.
The wreckage was found on a 3,000-meter-high plateau near Mammoth Lakes in the Sierra Nevada Mountains on the border of California and Nevada.
No human remains were found inside the aircraft.
John Anderson, sheriff of Madera County, said: “After determining the aircraft’s position, we sent a team out, and now we can be sure it’s the plane that Steve Fossett flew the day he disappeared.”
The sheriff also confirmed that no human remains were found in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was pronounced dead in February.
The U.S. Transportation Security Agency (NTSB) said it had asked a committee of inquiry a few hours after the wreck was discovered to identify the plane and establish that it was the Bellanca 8kcab that disappeared on September 3, 2007, the day Fossett left for a three-hour flight from Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, too, in California, not far from the Nevada border, a couple found some of Fossett's personal belongings near his Mammoth Lakes home.
Two I.D.s in Fosset's name issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, some cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was terminated a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire has set up numerous peaks through which he has written himself into history.
In 2002, on a sixth attempt, he first managed to fly around the earth with a balloon: two weeks of solitary flight.
Three years later, he flew around the earth without landing.
Several of his records also include flying over the Andes at an altitude of 15,445 meters, which he performed with a co-pilot.
